[White "1... d5 without"]
[Black "...c5: 2... Bf5"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The London System"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-london-system/course/5774, variation/228697"]

1. d4 d5 {1...d5 Intro ...d5 is Black's *most classical* response to the Closed 
Games. Black makes no attempt to unbalance the game right out of the gate but 
rather prefers to play solid and safe chess. ...d5 is a bit *more committal* 
than the super-flexible ...Nf6, but it does have a few exclusive openings that 
are unique to ...d5, such as the Queen's Gambit Accepted} ({note that the QGA is 
only possible after} d5 2. c4 {, which is not covered here}) {. ...d5 is Black's 
*second most common* retort to 1. d4 after Nf6. Variation Breakdown I have 
divided the ...d5 chapters into two: those *variations/setups with ...c5* and 
those *without.* I thought this was the simplest way to divide the content as 
there are a vast array of *different move orders* that Black can utilise. 
Transpositions are rife in the London, especially after ...d5, so please be 
aware of this. I decided to cover Black's ...c5 setups after c5, although he can 
reach the same positions by playing ...Nf6, ...e6 first etc. If Black doesn't 
opt for ...c5, he can choose between ...Bf5 ideas or Chigorin plans (involving 
...Nc6). Black can also go into a 'triangle' setup with ...e6 and ...c6, but 
this is hardly dangerous since White gets a free hand to play e4 at some point 
while Black lacks counterplay.} 2. Bf4 ({One of the standard 'London moves'. As 
previously mentioned, White can typically make use of multiple move orders, such 
as playing} 2. Nf3 {and 3. Bf4. I prefer the 2. Bf4 move order as it is often 
beneficial for White to delay developing the kingside knight.}) ({Note that 
White's most popular move here is of course the Queen's Gambit} 2. c4 {, which 
should objectively challenge Black more but it also requires greater theoretical 
knowledge.}) Bf5 {Even if this is hardly going to be the London's refutation, it 
is important to check what to do if Black 'copies' white. 2... Bf5 is perfectly 
natural, as there doesn't seem to be a way to immediately exploit it.} 3. e3 
({Once again, delaying the development of the kingside knight is more flexible 
than} 3. Nf3 {.}) e6 {Black continues to 'copy'.} 4. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3f5][%csl Rf5] 
Carlsen's choice when he played white in this position and I think it is White's 
best chance to unbalance the position. If Black takes on d3, he activates our 
queen, and if he retreats to g6 then we have developed our bishop to d3 with 
tempo.} Bxd3 ({Black's most popular response is to simply take the bishop. If he 
retreats with} 4... Bg6 {, then White has developed with tempo and he can 
continue with} 5. Nf3 {- possible Ne5 is an idea - and 6. O-O.}) 5. Qxd3 {[%cal 
Bd3b5,Gb5e8,Gb5b7][%csl Rb7] We recapture with the queen of course. From this 
position, White threatens Qb5+ to win the b7-pawn.} c6 {This is a natural move 
played to prevent the Qb5+ threat.} 6. Nd2 {[%cal Ge3e4] Maybe this is a 
slightly preferable move order to Nf3 first. White makes Black think about an 
early e4 advance.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4]} 7. Ngf3 $11 {[%cal 
Gc2c4,Ge3e4,Bf8d6,Bf4g5,Be1g1] The position is close to equal, but white still 
retains a slight pull. To White's benefit is the fact that he is ahead in 
development and has the possibility of carrying out the e4 and c4 breaks at some 
point. It is also important to note that White should meet ...Bd6 with Bg5 - we 
want to keep pieces on the board. For a good model game on how to play this 
position, I recommend taking a look at how Carlsen beat Giri from this position 
in 2016.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The London System"]
[Site "S&S: The London System"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1... d5 without"]
[Black "...c5: 2... Nc6"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The London System"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-london-system/course/5774, variation/228696"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 ({One of the standard 'London moves'. As previously mentioned, 
White can typically make use of multiple move orders, such as playing} 2. Nf3 
{and 3. Bf4. I prefer the 2. Bf4 move order as it is often beneficial for White 
to delay developing the kingside knight.}) ({Note that White's most popular move 
here is of course the Queen's Gambit} 2. c4 {, which should objectively 
challenge Black more but it also requires greater theoretical knowledge.}) Nc6 
{[%cal Gc6e5,Be7e5] This move signifies the beginning of Black's Chigorin 
defence. Although the Chigorin is typically employed against 2. c4, sometimes 
Black decides to use the same setup against the London. I don't believe it is 
quite as effective here and I actually think the knight is a bit misplaced on 
c6. The knight attempts to put pressure on d4 and possibly support a future 
...e5 lever, but the London seems to combat both of these things. By not playing 
c4 (not playing it early, at least) Black gets no counterplay against d4 because 
Black's pawn on d5 blocks the queen. Additionally, the bishop on f4 does well to 
control the e5-square.} 3. e3 {[%cal Bg1f3,Bc2c3,Bb1d2,Bf1d3] After reading my 
comment to the previous move, it should come as no surprise that I recommend 
avoiding c4 for quite some time. e3 is a solid, flexible move which protects d4 
and allows White to complete his development.} Nf6 4. Nf3 {[%cal 
Gf3e5,Gf4e5,Gd4e5][%csl Ge5] White just wants to get his king to safety now.} 
Bg4 {A nice, active square for the bishop. The pin is a little bit unpleasant 
for White.} 5. Nbd2 {White continues to develop without hamstringing any future 
plans with the c-pawn. Of course, the knight is misplaced on c3, so it rather 
goes to d2.} e6 6. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4,Gf4h2][%csl Rg4] No harm in pushing Black's 
bishop back while making space for our dark-squared bishop on h2.} Bh5 7. c3 
{[%cal Gc3b4,Bf1d3][%csl Gb4] c3 is played to take away the b4-square from the 
knight on c6. ...Nb4 could be a bit unpleasant when we go Bd3.} Bd6 {Black 
offers the exchange of dark-squared bishops.} 8. Bd3 $11 {[%cal 
Bd6f4,Be3f4,Gf3e5,Ge1e5][%csl Ge5] The best square for our light-squared bishop, 
but notice how we meet ...Bd6 in this case. Instead of Bg3 or Bxd6, we keep the 
bishop on f4 with no fear of ...Bxf4.} ({I'd like to take this opportunity to 
briefly explain the structure after} 8. Bd3 8... Bxf4 9. exf4 {. The doubled 
f-pawns provide White with complete control over the e5 outpost as well as the 
semi-open e-file for one of White's rooks. In the future, White can play the f5 
break to open up the e-file. All in all, this structure should be quite 
favourable to White.}) *

