bishops.} 7. Bg3 {As mentioned previously, this is the standard response to 
...Bd6. White retreats his bishop to g3 to avoid ...Bxf4. The alternative, Bxd6, 
activates Black's queen unnecessarily. The queen on d6 protects c5 and helps 
support a possible ...e5 break.} O-O 8. Bd3 {[%cal Be3e4] Simple development. 
The bishop is far better on d3 of course since it helps support an e4 break, 
which is one of White's main plans in the London.} b6 9. e4 {[%cal Be4e5][%csl 
Rd6,Rf6] White carries out his standard e4-break.} Be7 $1 {[%cal Re4e5] Black's 
best option - he retreats the bishop to avoid the threatened e5-fork.} 10. dxc5 
({White's most common choice here is also the most natural -} 10. e5 {. I do 
think this is a bit inaccurate though. Although White appears to have great 
kingside attacking chances, I think this is misleading. Not only is it 
physically tricky to get White's pieces over to the kingside, but Black also has 
...f5 which basically stops White's attack in in its tracks.}) {Instead, 10. 
dxc5 gives White a chance to unbalance the pawn structure and play along the 
d-file.} bxc5 11. O-O $11 {[%cal Bd1c2,Ba1d1,Bf1e1,Ge1e8,Gd1d8] White gets his 
king to safety. Next White intends to finish his development and begin playing 
with his rooks on the central files.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The London System"]
[Site "S&S: The London System"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1... d5 with ...c5: 5... Qb6"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The London System"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-london-system/course/5774, variation/228703"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 ({One of the standard 'London moves'. As previously mentioned, 
White can typically make use of multiple move orders, such as playing} 2. Nf3 
{and 3. Bf4. I prefer the 2. Bf4 move order as it is often beneficial for White 
to delay developing the kingside knight.}) ({Note that White's most popular move 
here is of course the Queen's Gambit} 2. c4 {, which should objectively 
challenge Black more but it also requires greater theoretical knowledge.}) c5 
{As I've mentioned multiple times, the London is rife with transpositions. I 
have decided to cover all variations with ...c5 under this c5 move order. I 
reckon it is one of Black's most challenging variations objectively. Black 
reasons that if White doesn't play the Queen's Gambit, he will!} 3. e3 ({I spent 
a long time analysing this variation. My initial choice was} 3. Nc3 {but that 
ran into some concrete problems after} Nc6 4. e4 cxd4 5. exd5 dxc3 6. dxc6 Qxd1+ 
7. Rxd1 bxc6 {. The variation ends up in an endgame where White is active but 
Black has a better pawn structure. Since it is very equal, I have decided not to 
recommend this as the main choice for the repertoire. Note that it still is an 
interesting and decent option, but just the fact that it results in an equal 
endgame within a few moves rules it out as my main recommendation.}) {3. e3 is 
the most common choice of White and keeps plenty of possibilities on the board.} 
Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 ({I have a specific reason for choosing this move order 
as opposed to 5. c3. The point is to counter ...Qb6. After} 5. c3 Qb6 $1 {is 
awkward. I think Qb3 never really favours White in this variation and the 
alternatives appear very passive.}) {Instead, 5. Nbd2 is a move White usually 
makes anyway, but now we can sacrifice a pawn against ...Qb6 to make the play 
very interesting.} Qb6 {[%cal Gb6b2][%csl Rb2] Of course, this is one of Black's 
critical options - Black hits b2.} 6. dxc5 {[%csl Gc5,Gb2,Rb6] The point - Black 
can't recapture both pawns simultaneously, so we take advantage of this.} Qxb2 
{If Black takes the other pawn instead White is simply better. He can develop 
and castle. The problem there for Black is his exposed queen. White can gain a 
handful of tempi against the queen, thus further increasing his development 
lead.} 7. Rb1 Qc3 8. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5e8,Be1g1,Bf3e5,Bf3d4][%csl Rc6,Re8] White 
can't protect c5, but there's no need. White's development advantage has grown 
enough for White to be capable of sacrificing the pawn.} e6 ({Black prioritises 
development over grabbing the c5-pawn, as he should. After} 8... Qxc5 {White can 
begin to open the position to his advantage with} 9. c4 $1 {.}) 9. O-O {[%cal 
Rf8c5,Gf4e5][%csl Rc5]} Be7 ({Note that} 9... Bxc5 {runs into the highly 
unpleasant} 10. Be5 $1 {.}) 10. Ne5 $11 {[%cal Bb5c6,Be5c6][%csl Bc6]} ({White 
has good play in this position for the pawn. For example, play could continue} 
10. Ne5 10... Qxc5 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. c4 $1 {, which opens up the c-file for 
White's rooks.}) *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The London System"]
[Site "S&S: The London System"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queen's Indian Setups:"]
[Black "...c5 with ...d6"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The London System"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-london-system/course/5774, variation/228430"]

1. d4 Nf6 {Black's most flexible move, and as a result also his most popular 
choice. Black takes e4 under his control, thus preventing White from making that 
move himself. From here, Black can develop in a number of ways: ...g6 plans, 
...e6 plans or ...c5 ideas, or he can somtimes revert back to a ...d5 variation! 
I have divided the course into lines covering each of these different systems 
Black has.} 2. Bf4 {A variety of different move orders can be used in the 
London, each with their own pros and cons. The one I have chosen against Nf6 is 
2. Bf4. The other London move order is 2. Nf3 followed by 3. Bf4. My reason for 
choosing 2. Bf4 is because of my response to the ...g6 systems, which will be 
revealed in those lines.} ({The supposed downside to playing this} 2. Bf4 {move 
order is} 2... c5 {. This is one of the variations where I deviate from standard 
London procedure - e3, c3, Nf3 and the like - and opt for} 3. d5 {instead. The 
positions are interesting and fresh with good chances for both sides.}) e6 {A 
flexible choice by Black. While this usually signifies the beginning of the 
Nimzo-Indian defence, it can often transpose to Queen's Gambit Declined setups 
or even Benoni setups.} 3. e3 {A standard move. Since we are playing the London, 
we'd prefer not to commit our pawn to c4 too early or at all. Instead, White 
continues to develop his kingside and fortifies the d4-pawn.} b6 {This chapter 
will be dealing with Black's Queen's Indian Defence setup. This involves a 
fianchetto of Black's light-squared bishop along the diagonal. This is played 
with the idea of taking e4 under Black's control and pressuring White's 
kingside.} 4. Nf3 {Natural development. This is White's best option. It is too 
early to contest for the e4-square. Note that ...Nh5 is not a threat because of 
Bg5.} Bb7 5. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3e4] e2 is also a possible square for the bishop, but 
putting just a little bit of pressure on e4 can go a long way to wresting 
control over that square from Black. Once again ...Nh5 is not a threat on 
account of Bg5.} Be7 {[%cal Bf6h5][%csl Rf4] Black takes the d8-h4 diagonal 
under his control and now ...Nh5 is a real threat to gain the bishop pair.} 6. 
h3 $1 {[%cal Gf4h2] Of course, we don't want to give away the bishop pair for 
nothing. h3 makes the h2 retreat square available for White's bishop. Please be 
aware that Black can choose from a plethora of move orders in this position. He 
can play ...d5 and ...c5, followed by taking on d4, or play ...c5, take on d4 
and then play ...d5 etc. I have covered 3 variations from this position: • 
...d5 + ...c5; • ...d5 and Black takes on d4 after ...c5; • ...c5 and Black 
plays ...d6 - he takes on d4 at some point.} c5 {One of the many move orders 
Black can choose. In most cases though, ...c5 features in Black's plans at some 
point.} 7. O-O O-O 8. c3 {[%csl Bd4] Reinforcing d4.} d6 $5 {[%cal 
Bb7e4,Re6e5,Gb1d2,Ge3e4] In this variation black chooses to go into a slightly 
more dynamic pawn structure based on d6 and e6 pawns instead of d5 and e6 pawns. 
This means that the bishop on b7 remains active and the ...e5 break is a remote 
possibility, but the big downside is that Black loses his stranglehold over the 
e4 square.} 9. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2e4,Gd3e4] The best square for the knight of 
course. From here it contributes to the fight for e4.} Nbd7 {Black remains 
flexible and refrains from taking on d4 immediately.} 10. a4 $1 {[%cal 
Ba4a5,Ba5a6][%csl Rb6,Rb7] A standard motif - the central situation has ground 
to a standstill so white opens up a new frontier on the queenside with a4-a5. 
This a-pawn lever also has good practical value, since often a-pawn marches 
appear to be stronger than they usually are. This results in an opponent 
spending more time and possibly even being frightened into an error, such as 
...bxa5.} a6 {[%cal Ba4a5,Gb6b5] A fairly standard response. Black intends to 
meet a5 with ...b5.} 11. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Bb2b4,Bc3c4,Be3e4,Ge2a6][%csl Ra6] White 
stands a bit better in this position. There's clearly plenty of play here for 
both sides, since nothing has been exchanged so far! Black's play here seems 
mostly reactive while White is the one who has various options of how to make 
use of his centre. White might wants to play e4 at some point or maybe even b4 
or c4. What's clear though is that White's extra space and central control grant 
him the edge here.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The London System"]
[Site "S&S: The London System"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queen's Indian Setups:"]
[Black "...d5 ...c5 with ...cxd4"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The London System"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-london-system/course/5774, variation/228428"]

1. d4 Nf6 {Black's most flexible move, and as a result also his most popular 
choice. Black takes e4 under his control, thus preventing White from making that 
move himself. From here, Black can develop in a number of ways: ...g6 plans, 
...e6 plans or ...c5 ideas, or he can somtimes revert back to a ...d5 variation! 
I have divided the course into lines covering each of these different systems 
Black has.} 2. Bf4 {A variety of different move orders can be used in the 
London, each with their own pros and cons. The one I have chosen against Nf6 is 
2. Bf4. The other London move order is 2. Nf3 followed by 3. Bf4. My reason for 
choosing 2. Bf4 is because of my response to the ...g6 systems, which will be 
revealed in those lines.} ({The supposed downside to playing this} 2. Bf4 {move 
order is} 2... c5 {. This is one of the variations where I deviate from standard 
London procedure - e3, c3, Nf3 and the like - and opt for} 3. d5 {instead. The 
positions are interesting and fresh with good chances for both sides.}) e6 {A 
flexible choice by Black. While this usually signifies the beginning of the 
Nimzo-Indian defence, it can often transpose to Queen's Gambit Declined setups 
or even Benoni setups.} 3. e3 {A standard move. Since we are playing the London, 
we'd prefer not to commit our pawn to c4 too early or at all. Instead, White 
continues to develop his kingside and fortifies the d4-pawn.} b6 {This chapter 
will be dealing with Black's Queen's Indian Defence setup. This involves a 
fianchetto of Black's light-squared bishop along the diagonal. This is played 
with the idea of taking e4 under Black's control and pressuring White's 
kingside.} 4. Nf3 {Natural development. This is White's best option. It is too 
early to contest for the e4-square. Note that ...Nh5 is not a threat because of 
Bg5.} Bb7 {[%cal Bb7e4,Bf6e4]} 5. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3e4] e2 is also a possible square 
for the bishop, but putting just a little bit of pressure on e4 can go a long 
way to wresting control over that square from Black. Once again ...Nh5 is not a 
threat on account of Bg5.} Be7 {[%cal Rd8h4,Rf6h5][%csl Rf4] Black takes the 
d8-h4 diagonal under his control and now ...Nh5 is a real threat to gain the 
bishop pair.} 6. h3 $1 {[%cal Bf4h2] Of course, we don't want to give away the 
bishop pair for nothing. h3 makes the h2 retreat square available for White's 
bishop. Please be aware that Black can choose from a plethora of move orders in 
this position. He can play ...d5 and ...c5, followed by taking on d4, or play 
...c5, take on d4 and then play ...d5 etc. I have covered 3 variations from this 
position: • ...d5 + ...c5; • ...d5 and Black takes on d4 after ...c5; • 
...c5 and Black plays ...d6 - he takes on d4 at some point.} d5 {[%cal 
Bd5e4][%csl Be4] Black's most solid and objectively best option. ...d5 should 
probably be played at some point since Black needs to retain his control over 
e4. If he doesn't then White can just go for Nbd2 and e4 himself.} 7. O-O O-O 
{Nothing too fancy from either sides.} 8. Nbd2 {[%cal Bd2e4] Note that I prefer 
to delay playing c3 only once Black has played ...c5. This gives White the extra 
option of c4 in the event of Black moves like ...Ne4.} c5 9. c3 {White 
solidifies his d4 pawn and makes the c2 and b1 squares available for White's 
bishop and queen.} cxd4 {This capture is played quite often, although based on 
my analysis it is best for black to avoid it and keep the tension. The change in 
structure benefits White.} 10. exd4 $14 {[%cal Bf3e5,Gf1e1,Ge1e5][%csl Be5] I 
think that this recapture is in most cases preferable to cxd4, although both are 
decent options. exd4 has the advantage of unbalancing the pawn structure a bit 
which is always nice. White's outpost on e5 gains in value, since evicting a 
knight from e5 with ...f6 would leave e6 drastically weakened. Also, the extra 
kingside space and semi-open e-file suit White's bishops. White will be trying 
to mostly play on the kingside and in the centre on account of his extra space.} 
*

