[White "...g6 Setups:"]
[Black "3...d5 with 5...Bxh6"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The London System"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-london-system/course/5774, variation/228426"]

1. d4 Nf6 {Black's most flexible move, and as a result also his most popular 
choice. Black takes e4 under his control, thus preventing White from making that 
move himself. From here, Black can develop in a number of ways: ...g6 plans, 
...e6 plans or ...c5 ideas, or he can somtimes revert back to a ...d5 variation! 
I have divided the course into lines covering each of these different systems 
Black has.} 2. Bf4 {A variety of different move orders can be used in the 
London, each with their own pros and cons. The one I have chosen against Nf6 is 
2. Bf4. The other London move order is 2. Nf3 followed by 3. Bf4. My reason for 
choosing 2. Bf4 is because of my response to the ...g6 systems, which will be 
revealed in those lines.} ({The supposed downside to playing this} 2. Bf4 {move 
order is} 2... c5 {. This is one of the variations where I deviate from standard 
London procedure - e3, c3, Nf3 and the like - and opt for} 3. d5 {instead. The 
positions are interesting and fresh with good chances for both sides.}) g6 
{Black's kingside fianchetto can lead to the very popular King's Indian and 
Grunfeld defences. KID players often go for ...c5 ideas against the London 
whereas Grunfeld players normally opt for the solid ...d5. However, there is a 
reason I have grouped them both together in one chapter: Black won't have the 
chance to reach his pet defences!} 3. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Be2e4] An unpleasant idea 
which makes Black think from the get-go. I know this from personal experience - 
I fell victim to this idea, since I had no good idea how to meet it. Upon 
reviewing this move, I realised that it is surprisingly popular and has been 
used by some strong players recently. White's idea is simple: he threatens e4 
and intends to develop rapidly. The plan is to exploit Black's fianchetto with 
Qd2 and Bh6 at some point, followed by possibly long-castling and launching a 
kingside attack.} d5 {[%cal Gd5e4] Black stops e4 in its tracks, but as I 
realised in my game here as Black, this move also makes the creation of 
counterplay significantly trickier since the ...c5 and ...e5 advances lose punch 
with a pawn on d5.} 4. Qd2 {[%cal Bf4h6,Be1c1] White is of course planning to 
play Bh6 at some point (to exchange Black's dark-squared bishop) and possibly 
castle long. This was reached in my game, and I recall that I was thinking 
deeply as Black already. Even though the evaluation for this variation is 
hovering somewhere between equal and very slightly better for White, it is 
highly unpleasant for Black, especially if unprepared for it.} Bg7 {The natural 
developing move.} 5. Bh6 {[%csl Rg7] White carries out his plan of exchanging 
Black's dark-squared bishop. That bishop plays a pivotal role both in the 
defence of Black's kingside and the attack on the long dark diagonal.} Bxh6 
{Taking on h6 and foregoing castling is played with the idea of exploiting the 
queen's slightly misplaced position on h6.} 6. Qxh6 Bf5 {[%csl Rc2]} ({Black's 
best and most active option. He exploits the fact that White's queen is on h6 
and attacks the c2-pawn. Note that it's Black's only move which achieves 
equality here. Black's most common choice,} 6... c5 {, is well-met by} 7. dxc5 
Qa5 8. a3 {with a good position.}) {Instead, after Bf5 Black must tread a fine 
line to emerge equal.} 7. O-O-O ({Long castling is natural and probably best. I 
think Jobava's choice of} 7. Qd2 {might be a bit too passive,}) ({while the pawn 
sacrifice} 7. f3 {leads to interesting play, but it seems to be more dangerous 
for White than Black.}) Ng4 {[%csl Rf2,Rh6]} ({This has only been played once, 
but it's Black's only path to equality! I'm sure many black players were scared 
by} Ng4 8. Qg7 {, but this isn't as dangerous as it appears -} 8... Rf8 9. Nh3 
e6 {etc. The h7-pawn is invulnerable because of ...Qf6 followed by ...Rh8, 
trapping White's queen.}) {If black doesn't choose Ng4, White will play 8. f3 
followed by 9. g4.} 8. Qf4 {[%cal Bf4f2]} ({As already mentioned,} 8. Qg7 
{appears promising but it underperforms.}) Qd6 {[%cal Bd6f4][%csl Rf2] Once 
again Black's only move to equalise. Black needs to take advantage of his brief 
initiative to push White back.} 9. Qf3 {Swapping queens is fine and perfectly 
playable, but I'm sure many players would rather avoid heading to an equal 
ending so early on in the game.} Nf6 {The knight has fulfilled its role on g4 
and returns to its ideal square.} 10. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4][%csl Gg4] h3 is a good, 
multi-purpose move. It bars Black's minor pieces access to the g4 square and 
possibly toys with the idea of lunging with the pawn to g4.} Nc6 11. e3 $11 
{[%cal Bf3e2,Be2d2,Gg1f3,Gf1d3] The position is roughly equal with chances for 
both sides in an interesting and fresh position. White needs to decide now how 
to complete development. One possible idea is to drop the queen back so that the 
knight has access to f3.} *

