1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 {This is a tricky move order Black has at his disposal, 
which means that we need to offer a second option for White against the 
Grunfeld.} 3. e3 {This is what we play, expecting Black to play as in the ...d5 
...c5 chapter.} g6 $1 ({But Black can defy expectations and transpose into a 
Grunfeld system! Now we would be out of our repertoire normally, since we play} 
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Qd2 {, which is clearly impossible now. 
However, there is another, equally good option instead of 4. Qd2: 4. e3.}) 4. 
Nc3 $1 {We transpose into 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3. Being unable to play 4. Qd2 seems 
like a concession, but it isn't really, since the options are roughly equally 
good. Covering this option has the added benefit of giving you an extra weapon 
against Grunfeld systems. You can learn both 4. Qd2 and 4. e3 to add some 
variety to your repertoire, or if you want to cut down on theory, you can pause 
the 4. Qd2 lines in Chessable and only learn 4. e3.} Bg7 5. h4 $1 {Naturally, 
one of the ideas of playing e3 is allow the queen to support an h4-h5 pawn rush. 
These h-pawn levers can be very unpleasant to deal with in practice, especially 
if unprepared.} c6 {Preventing any Nb5 ideas and supporting d5 while delaying 
castling.} 6. Be2 {[%cal Bh4h5,Gd1h5] The immediate h5 followed by an exchange 
sacrifice seems fun and it does bring good practical results, but objectively 
Black is better there with accurate play. Instead, Be2 is better to prepare h5.} 
h5 {Blocking h5.} 7. Nf3 {[%cal Bf3e5][%csl Ge5]} O-O 8. Ne5 {A typical idea in 
this variation, which is often followed up with f3 at some point.} Nbd7 9. Qd2 
$14 {[%cal Be1c1,Bf2f3,Bg2g4] White's harmonious development gives him a slight 
edge here.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The London System"]
[Site "S&S: The London System"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Benoni Setups: 3... d6"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The London System"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-london-system/course/5774, variation/228704"]

1. d4 Nf6 {Black's most flexible move, and as a result also his most popular 
choice. Black takes e4 under his control, thus preventing White from making that 
move himself. From here, Black can develop in a number of ways: ...g6 plans, 
...e6 plans or ...c5 ideas, or he can somtimes revert back to a ...d5 variation! 
I have divided the course into lines covering each of these different systems 
Black has.} 2. Bf4 {A variety of different move orders can be used in the 
London, each with their own pros and cons. The one I have chosen against Nf6 is 
2. Bf4. The other London move order is 2. Nf3 followed by 3. Bf4. My reason for 
choosing 2. Bf4 is because of my response to the ...g6 systems, which will be 
revealed in those lines.} ({The supposed downside to playing this} 2. Bf4 {move 
order is} 2... c5 {. This is one of the variations where I deviate from standard 
London procedure - e3, c3, Nf3 and the like - and opt for} 3. d5 {instead. The 
positions are interesting and fresh with good chances for both sides.}) c5 
{[%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4] Benoni setups against d4 are typically characterised by 
...c5 and a kingside fianchetto at some point. By playing ...c5, Black puts 
quick pressure on d4 and forces White to make a call: advance the pawn or 
protect it. Note that taking on c5 is not great since White can't really hold 
onto the pawn, which means he is simply ceding the centre for no good reason. 
This move, c5, is supposed to be the big downside of the 2. Bf4 London move 
order, although I don't really see it. The Benoni is one of the variations where 
I am deviating from the standard London recipe (i.e. e3, c3, Nf3 etc.). Instead, 
I will be advocating 3. d5. This might seem like a transposition into the 
Queen's Gambit variations, but the position does retain a distinct London 
flavour with the bishop on f4 instead of a pawn on c4.} 3. d5 $1 {[%cal 
Bg1f3,Gf3d2,Gd2c4][%csl Gc4,Gd5] By having the bishop on f4 instead of a pawn on 
c4, there are a few key differences between the positions of the Queen's Gambit 
and the London Benoni. Firstly, not having the pawn on c4 is in many ways an 
advantage. The c4 square is much better used for White's knight. Typically, 
white reroutes his kingside knight to c4 via f3 and d2. From here the knight 
eyes the d6 pawn and supports an e5 advance. Secondly, not having the pawn on c4 
reduces White's control over b5. This means that black may exploit this with 
...b5. Fortunately, this variation isn't too great, as I'll demonstrate in a 
short while. Thirdly, having the bishop on f4 instead of c1 means that b2 is 
hanging. Black can try exploit this with Qb6, which will be one of the 
variations that I cover.} d6 ({A very natural move and Black's second most 
common choice after} 3... Qb6 {.}) 4. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Gg1f3,Gf3d2,Gd2c4] Remember: 
the omission of c4 is a good thing! This means that the c4 square is free for 
our knight which will be routed there via f3 and d2.} g6 5. e4 Bg7 6. Nf3 {The 
obvious and best square for the knight.} O-O 7. a4 $14 {[%cal 
Ga4b5,Bf3d2,Bd2c4][%csl Gb5,Gc4] An important prophylactic move against ...b5. 
The Benoni is full of tactics and if White isn't careful he might fall victim to 
some ...b5 tricks - sometimes the b5 pawn is sacrificed to deflect White's 
knight from the defence of e4, in conjunction with ...Qa5+ motifs. Now that 
Black's ...b5 plan has been nipped in the bud, White can complete development 
and castle. Long-term he is looking to build up an initiative and carry out 
either the e5 or the b4 break.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The London System"]
[Site "S&S: The London System"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Benoni Setups: 3... b5"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The London System"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-london-system/course/5774, variation/228705"]

